      <aside class="calc-sidebar">
        <div class="card sidebar-card">
          <h2>GCD vs LCM</h2>
          <p><strong>GCD (Greatest Common Divisor)</strong> — also called HCF or GCF — is the largest number that divides all the given numbers exactly. Used to simplify fractions and solve sharing problems.<br><br><strong>LCM (Least Common Multiple)</strong> is the smallest number that is a multiple of all the given numbers. Used to add fractions with different denominators.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card sidebar-card">
          <h3>Frequently asked questions</h3>
          <details>
            <summary>What is the GCD of 12 and 18?</summary>
            <p>The GCD of 12 and 18 is 6, because 6 is the largest number that divides both 12 and 18 exactly (12÷6=2, 18÷6=3).</p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary>What method does this calculator use?</summary>
            <p>It uses the Euclidean algorithm for GCD, which is the most efficient method. The LCM is then calculated from the GCD using the formula LCM(a,b) = a×b ÷ GCD(a,b).</p>
          </details>
          <details>
            <summary>Can I calculate GCD and LCM of more than two numbers?</summary>
            <p>Yes. Enter any number of values separated by commas. The calculator applies the algorithm iteratively across all values.</p>
          </details>
